Product Requirements Document (PRD)
Product Name: AI-Powered Patient Data Management System
Version: 1.0
Date: October 2025
Author: Raj Kumar Rawat
Status: Draft
1.0 Executive Summary
1.1 Purpose
This PRD defines the requirements for an AI-Powered Patient Data Management System (PDMS)
designed to optimize healthcare record handling, automate patient data workflows, ensure compliance with
global regulations (HIPAA, GDPR, SOC2), and provide advanced analytics to healthcare professionals.
1.2 Objectives
• Centralize patient records with AI-assisted categorization and retrieval.
• Enable secure, compliant data storage and access control.
• Provide insights through predictive analytics and reporting dashboards.
• Facilitate integrations with hospital systems and third-party APIs.
2.0 Stakeholders & User Personas
2.1 Stakeholders
• Healthcare Administrators: Oversee compliance, data security, and efficiency.
• Medical Practitioners: Need real-time access to accurate patient histories.
• IT & Compliance Teams: Ensure data privacy and infrastructure stability.
• Patients: Expect secure handling and access to their medical data.
2.2 User Personas
1. Dr. Emily Carter (Physician): Needs quick insights into patient data before consultation.
2. John Patel (IT Admin): Manages user roles, access permissions, and audit logs.
3. Lisa Wong (Nurse): Updates patient vitals and treatment records daily.
4. Michael Green (Patient): Accesses personal records and lab results online.
3.0 Functional Requirements
Each requirement follows the format REQ-[CATEGORY]-[NUMBER] and uses modal verbs like shall, must,
or should.
1
3.1 Authentication & Authorization
• REQ-AUTH-001: The system shall support role-based access control (RBAC).
• REQ-AUTH-002: Users must authenticate via secure OAuth 2.0 and MFA.
• REQ-AUTH-003: The system shall allow session timeout after 15 minutes of inactivity.
3.2 Data Management
• REQ-DATA-001: The system shall securely store patient data in an encrypted database.
• REQ-DATA-002: Users must be able to upload patient documents (PDF, DICOM, CSV).
• REQ-DATA-003: The AI module shall automatically categorize patient data by type and relevance.
3.3 Dashboard & Reporting
• REQ-DASH-001: The dashboard should display patient summaries, trends, and alerts.
• REQ-DASH-002: The system must generate real-time analytics reports for physicians.
• REQ-DASH-003: Users shall export reports in PDF, Excel, or JSON formats.
3.4 Alerts & Notifications
• REQ-ALRT-001: The system shall notify practitioners of abnormal lab values.
• REQ-ALRT-002: Patients should receive appointment and prescription reminders.
3.5 Integration
• REQ-INTEG-001: The system shall integrate with EHR platforms via HL7 and FHIR APIs.
• REQ-INTEG-002: The platform must support integration with third-party diagnostic systems.
(30 total functional requirements will follow similar formatting across modules such as search, audit, AI insights,
and compliance.)
4.0 Non-Functional Requirements
1. The system shall respond within 5 seconds for standard queries.
2. The uptime shall be at least 99.9%.
3. The platform must comply with HIPAA, GDPR, SOC 2.
4. All user data should be encrypted using AES-256.
5. The interface should be accessible via WCAG 2.1 standards.
6. The system should support horizontal scalability.
7. Logs shall be retained for 7 years for audit purposes.
8. The API latency shall not exceed 300ms under normal load.
9. The system should maintain auditability for every data change.
10. The UI shall support localization in 5 languages.
2
5.0 Compliance Requirements
Each compliance requirement explicitly references the regulation and article number.
5.1 HIPAA Compliance
• HIPAA §164.312(a)(1): Implement access control and unique user identification.
• HIPAA §164.312(e)(1): Ensure data integrity during transmission.
5.2 GDPR Compliance
• GDPR Article 17: Right to erasure – users can request data deletion.
• GDPR Article 32: Implement appropriate technical and organizational measures for security.
5.3 SOC 2 Compliance
• SOC 2 CC6.1: Logical access controls must prevent unauthorized access.
Traceability Links:
• REQ-AUTH-001 → HIPAA §164.312(a)(1)
• REQ-DATA-001 → GDPR Article 32
• REQ-ALRT-001 → SOC 2 CC6.1
6.0 Integration Requirements
• The system shall connect with hospital EHR systems (EPIC, Cerner).
• Integration via FHIR/HL7 APIs for interoperability.
• Support external analytics via REST and GraphQL endpoints.
7.0 Testing Requirements
Each functional module shall undergo:
• Unit Testing: Validate individual functions.
• Integration Testing: Verify module interoperability.
• User Acceptance Testing (UAT): Conducted by hospital staff and administrators.
Acceptance Criteria:
• Response time ≤ 5 seconds.
• 100% encryption validation in data flow.
• Successful integration with at least one EHR sandbox.
3
8.0 Assumptions
1. Hospitals have stable internet and API infrastructure.
2. Data will be primarily in English for the first release.
3. All users are trained in digital medical record handling.
9.0 Dependencies
1. Cloud hosting on AWS or Azure.
2. Third-party identity management (Okta/Auth0).
3. EHR partner sandbox access.
10.0 Risks
Risk
Impact
Mitigation
AI misclassification
Medium
Manual review option for flagged data
API downtime
High
Caching and fallback endpoints
Compliance breach
High
Regular audits and encryption checks
11.0 Future Enhancements
• Support for multilingual AI summarization.
• Blockchain-based patient data verification.
• Integration with wearable health devices.
12.0 Conclusion
The AI-Powered Patient Data Management System shall modernize medical record handling, streamline
operations, and maintain compliance. With AI-driven insights and automation, it aims to reduce
administrative load and improve patient outcomes while ensuring top-tier data security and scalability.
